is there a key you can press to view all mywindows at same time on fedora 42?
ChatGPT said:

Yep — Fedora 42 (GNOME desktop) has a built-in “Activities Overview” that’ll show all your open windows in a single view.

Here’s how to trigger it:

Keyboard shortcut:

  • Super key (Windows key on most keyboards) → tap once to enter Activities Overview.

  • You’ll see all your open windows tiled out.

Extra tricks:

  • Super + Tab → Switch between open apps in that overview style.

  • Super + ↑ → Maximize the current window.

  • Super + ↓ → Restore or minimize the window.

  • Super + Left/Right Arrow → Snap window to half the screen.

  • Super + Page Up/Page Down → Switch workspaces vertically.

If you have multiple workspaces, Super + Alt + ↑/↓ will jump between them while still seeing your open windows.

Do you want me to also give you the touchpad/mouse gesture version so you can trigger it without the keyboard? That can be handy if your hands are on the mouse while juggling browser tabs and GitHub windows.

  • On a touchpad, use three-finger swipe up (if gestures are enabled in Settings → Mouse & Touchpad).

You said:
where is repo root on namecheap
ChatGPT said:

On Namecheap, there isn’t a “repo root” — that’s a GitHub thing.

Here’s how they connect:

  • Repo root = in GitHub, it’s the top-level folder of your project (where files like index.html, README.md, and the .git folder live).

  • That’s where you’d put the CNAME file so GitHub Pages knows to use reconrepairs.org.

On Namecheap, you never upload a CNAME file. Instead, you just update your DNS records so that your domain points to GitHub Pages.

So the sequence is:

  1. In Namecheap → Add the A records and CNAME record in the Advanced DNS tab.

  2. In GitHub → Put the CNAME file in your repo root (top level of your GitHub Pages repository) and commit it.

  1. Edit index.html in GitHub.

  2. Make sure the very top of your file looks exactly like this:

html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0"/>

  <style>
    /* all the CSS here */
  </style>
</head>
<body>

⚠️ The <style> tag must be between <head> and </head> — not after <body> starts.

  1. Scroll to the bottom of your <style> block and make sure it closes with </style> before the </head> tag.

  2. Commit changes → wait 30 seconds → refresh your site.
